# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chiplet-architecture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] A **2.5D integrated circuit** (**2.5D IC**) is an advanced packaging technique that combines multiple integrated circuit dies in a single package without stacking them into a three-dimensional integrated circuit (3D-IC) with through-silicon vias (TSVs).
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The term "2.5D" originated when 3D-ICs with TSVs were quite new and still very difficult.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Chip designers realized that many of the advantages of 3D integration could be approximated by placing bare dies side by side on an interposer instead of stacking them vertically.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] If the pitch is very fine and the interconnect very short, the assembly can be packaged as a single component with better size, weight, and power characteristics than a comparable 2D circuit board assembly.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] This half-way 3D integration was facetiously named "2.5D" and the name stuck.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] An interposer can support heterogeneous integration – that is, dies of different pitch, size, material, and process node.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Placing dies side by side instead of stacking them reduces heat buildup.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Upgrading or modifying a 2.5D assembly is as easy as swapping in a new component and revamping the interposer to suit; much faster and simpler than reworking an entire 3D-IC or System-on-Chip (SoC).
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Some sophisticated 2.5D assemblies even incorporate TSVs and 3D components.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Several foundries now support 2.5D packaging.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The success of 2.5D assembly has given rise to "chiplets" – small, functional circuit blocks designed to be combined in mix-and-match fashion on interposers.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Several high-end products already take advantage of these LEGO-style chiplets; some experts predict the emergence of an industry-wide chiplet ecosystem.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Interposers can be larger than the reticle size which is the maximum area that can be projected by a photolithography scanner or stepper.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] A 2.5D IC architecture is an intermediate solution between traditional 2D and advanced 3D architectures.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] While a 2D architecture integrates all components on a single silicon die (SoC) and a 3D architecture stacks multiple dies vertically, the 2.5D approach involves placing multiple chiplets side-by-side on a silicon interposer within a single package.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The chiplets, which perform various functions, are bonded to the interposer, and the interconnection between them are routed on this interposer.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The interposer is then connected to the package substrate using silicon vias, which provide connections to peripheral hardware such as SRAM or DRAM.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The interposer, also known as a redistributed layer (RDL), is a key component in the physical design of chiplets.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] It acts as an intermediate layer that facilitates communication between chiplets and provides interfaces for peripheral devices.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The design of the interposer and its wiring is crucial, as the routing of these wires can introduce additional latency and parasitic parameters that can affect overall performance and reliability.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] In advanced packaging technologies like CoWoS, the interposer design method uses wiring within the interposer and through-silicon-via (TSV) technology to connect chiplets and establish connections to the packaging substrate.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Interposers can be made from different materials, including silicon, glass, and organics.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Silicon interposers are widely used due to their ability to achieve fine feature sizes with existing process technology, making them a cost-effective option.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Interposers use TSVs for communication between the chip and for connecting to the substrate.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] A 10x100um TSV is sometimes used in an interposer with three or four metal layers on the probe side and a single copper RDL on the grind side.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] There are several interposer technologies used in 2.5D ICs, each with its own set of trade-offs in terms of cost, performance, and complexity.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The interconnects in a 2.5D IC, including micro-bumps and underfill materials, play an important role in the enablement of high bandwidth and low power consumption.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The signal channels in a 2.5D integration consist of I/O drivers and receivers, I/O pads, micro-bumps, and chip-to-chip wires.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The wires are horizontally routed on an interconnect carrier, such as a bridge-chip, stitch-chip, or an interposer.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The use of smaller pads and micro-bumps in technologies like HIST (Heterogeneous Interconnect Stitching Technology) and interposers leads to smaller capacitance, which improves electrical performance.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] For example, the total capacitance of a micro-bump and a pair of pads for HIST is about 18 times smaller than that of a bridge-chip because bridge-chip bumps also include organic package vias.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The reduced capacitance and shorter interconnects contribute to lower latency and energy consumption.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Furthermore, HIST and interposer-based solutions achieve the largest bandwidth-density (BWD) among 2.5D solutions due to the ultralow parasitics of micro-bumps and pads.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] While 2.5D IC technology offers numerous advantages, it also presents several challenges and limitations that must be addressed.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] 2.5D and 3D heterogeneous integration technologies are used in a variety of applications, particularly in high-performance computing (HPC), AI accelerators, high-end CPUs, and FPGAs.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] The development of industry standards is crucial for the widespread adoption of 2.5D and 3D integration technologies.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Some future trends in 2.5D and 3D integration include the use of bridge technologies and co-packaged optics.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Intel's Co-EMIB combines Foveros and EMIB to provide 2.5D and 3D connectivity between dies in a package, achieving high interconnect density in both horizontal and vertical directions.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Another example is the omnidirectional interconnect (ODI), which can support high-bandwidth interconnects and direct power delivery using smaller TSVs and high-bandwidth interconnects.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] Another approach is the use of photonic interconnects as a solution for high-bandwidth, low-power communication in 2.5D integrated systems.
[src:chiplet-architecture/2-5d-integrated-circuit] In this case an Arrayed Waveguide Grating Router (AWGR) can be used, for example, as an optical switch fabric to construct a photonic Network-on-Chip (NoC) for interposer-based implementations.
[src:chiplet-architecture/chiplet] A **chiplet** is a tiny integrated circuit (**IC**) that contains a well-defined subset of functionality.
[src:chiplet-architecture/chiplet] It is designed to be combined with other chiplets on an interposer in a single package to create a complex component such as a computer processor.
[src:chiplet-architecture/chiplet] Each chiplet in a computer processor provides only a portion of the processor's total functionality.
[src:chiplet-architecture/chiplet] A set of chiplets can be implemented in a mix-and-match "Lego-like" assembly.
[src:chiplet-architecture/chiplet] Multiple chiplets working together in a single integrated circuit may be called a multi-chip module, hybrid IC, 2.5D IC, or advanced package.
[src:chiplet-architecture/chiplet] Chiplets may be connected with standards such as UCIe, bunch of wires (BoW), AIB (Advanced Interface Bus), OpenHBI (Open High Bandwidth Interface), and OIF (Optical Internetworking Forum) XSR (Extra Short Reach).
[src:chiplet-architecture/chiplet] Chiplets not designed by the same company must be designed with interoperability in mind.
[src:chiplet-architecture/chiplet] The term was coined by University of California, Berkeley professor John Wawrzynek as a component of the RAMP Project (research accelerator for multiple processors) in 2006 extension for the Department of Energy.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] An **interposer** is an electrical interface routing between one socket or connection and another.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] The purpose of an interposer is to spread a connection to a wider pitch or to reroute a connection to a different connection.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] An interposer can be made of either silicon or organic (printed circuit board-like) material.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] Interposer comes from the Latin word *interpōnere*, meaning "to put between".
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] They are often used in BGA packages, multi-chip modules and high-bandwidth memory.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] A common example of an interposer is an integrated circuit die to BGA, such as in the Pentium II.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] This is done through various substrates, both rigid and flexible, most commonly FR4 for rigid, and polyimide for flexible.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] Silicon and glass are also evaluated as an integration method.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] Interposer stacks are also a widely accepted, cost-effective alternative to 3D ICs.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] There are already several products with interposer technology in the market, notably the AMD Fiji/Fury GPU, and the Xilinx Virtex-7 FPGA.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] In 2016, CEA Leti demonstrated their second-generation 3D-NoC technology, which combines small dies ("chiplets"), fabricated at the FDSOI 28 nm node, on a 65 nm CMOS interposer.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] Another example of an interposer is the adapter used to plug a SATA drive into a SAS backplane with redundant ports.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] While SAS drives have two ports that can be used to connect to redundant paths or storage controllers, SATA drives only have a single port.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] Directly, they can only connect to a single controller or path.
[src:chiplet-architecture/interposer] SATA drives can be connected to nearly all SAS backplanes without adapters, but using an interposer with a port-switching logic allows providing paths redundancy.
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] Other terms for MCM packaging include "heterogeneous integration" or "hybrid integrated circuit".
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] The advantage of using MCM packaging is it allows a manufacturer to use multiple components for modularity and/or to improve yields over a conventional monolithic IC approach.
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] A **Flip Chip Multi-Chip Module** (**FCMCM**) is a multi-chip module that uses flip chip technology.
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] A FCMCM may have one large die and several smaller dice all on the same module.
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] Multi-chip modules come in a variety of forms depending on the complexity and development philosophies of their designers.
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] These can range from using pre-packaged ICs on a small printed circuit board (PCB) meant to mimic the package footprint of an existing chip package to fully custom chip packages integrating many chip dies on a high density interconnection (HDI) substrate.
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] This is often either organic (a laminated circuit board that contains carbon, hence *organic*) or is made of silicon (as in High Bandwidth Memory).
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] Using interposers to connect several ICs instead of connecting several monolithic ICs in separate packages reduces the power needed to transmit signals between ICs, increases the number of transmission channels, and reduces delays caused by resistance and capacitance (RC delays).
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] However, communication between chiplets consumes more power and has higher latency than components within monolithic ICs.
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] A relatively new development in MCM technology is the so-called "chip-stack" package.
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] Certain ICs, memories in particular, have very similar or identical pinouts when used multiple times within systems.
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] A carefully designed substrate can allow these dies to be stacked in a vertical configuration making the resultant MCM's footprint much smaller (albeit at the cost of a thicker or taller chip).
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] Since area is more often at a premium in miniature electronics designs, the chip-stack is an attractive option in many applications such as cell phones and personal digital assistants (PDAs).
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] With the use of a 3D integrated circuit and a thinning process, as many as ten dies can be stacked to create a high capacity SD memory card.
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] This technique can also be used for High Bandwidth Memory.
[src:chiplet-architecture/multi-chip-module] The possible way to increasing the performance of data transfer in the Chip stack is use Wireless Networks on Chip (WiNoC).
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] During PCB assembly, the bottom package of a PoP stack is placed directly on the PCB, and the other package(s) of the stack are stacked on top.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] The packages of a PoP stack become attached to each other (and to the PCB) during reflow soldering.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] PoP packaging can be done by the chip manufacturer (such as Samsung or TSMC), or can be done by the OEM (such as Xiaomi).
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] The package on a package technique tries to combine the benefits of traditional packaging with the benefits of die-stacking techniques, while avoiding their drawbacks.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] Traditional packaging places each die in its own package, a package designed for normal PCB assembly techniques that place each package directly on the PCB side-by-side.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] The 3D die-stacking system in package (SiP) techniques stacks multiple die in a single package, which has several advantages and also some disadvantages compared to traditional PCB assembly.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] In embedded PoP techniques, chips are embedded in a substrate on the bottom of the package.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] This PoP technology enables smaller packages with shorter electrical connections and is supported by companies such as Advanced Semiconductor Engineering (ASE).
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] The most obvious benefit is motherboard space savings.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] PoP uses much less PCB area, almost as little as stacked-die packages.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] Electrically, PoP offers benefits by minimizing track length between different interoperating parts, such as a controller and memory.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] This yields better electrical performance of devices, since shorter routing of interconnections between circuits yields faster signal propagation and reduced noise and cross-talk.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] There are several key differences between stacked-die and stacked-package products.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] The main financial benefit of package on a package is that the memory device is decoupled from the logic device.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] In 2001, a Toshiba research team including T.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] Takubo developed a "System Block Module" wafer bonding process for manufacturing 3D integrated circuit (3D IC) packages.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] The earliest known commercial use of a 3D package-on-package chip was in Sony's PlayStation Portable (PSP) handheld game console, released in 2004.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] The PSP hardware includes eDRAM (embedded DRAM) memory manufactured by Toshiba in a 3D package chip with two dies stacked vertically.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] Toshiba called it "semi-embedded DRAM" at the time, before later calling it a stacked "chip-on-chip" (CoC) solution.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] In April 2007, Toshiba commercialized an eight-layer 3D chip package, the 16 GB THGAM embedded NAND flash memory chip, which was manufactured with eight stacked 2 GB NAND flash chips.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] The same month, U.S. patent 7,923,830 ("Package-on-package secure module having anti-tamper mesh in the substrate of the upper package") was filed by Steven M.
[src:chiplet-architecture/package-on-package] In September 2007, Hynix Semiconductor introduced 24-layer 3D packaging technology, with a 16 GB flash memory chip that was manufactured with 24 stacked NAND flash chips using a wafer bonding process.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] In electronic engineering, a **through-silicon via** (**TSV**) or **through-chip via** is a vertical electrical connection (via) that passes completely through a silicon wafer or die.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] TSVs are high-performance interconnect techniques used as an alternative to wire-bond and flip chips to create 3D packages and 3D integrated circuits.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] Compared to alternatives such as package-on-package, the interconnect and device density is substantially higher, and the length of the connections becomes shorter.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] Via-middle TSVs are currently a popular option for advanced 3D ICs as well as for interposer stacks.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] TSVs through the front end of line (FEOL) have to be carefully accounted for during the EDA and manufacturing phases.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] That is because TSVs induce thermo-mechanical stress in the FEOL layer, thereby impacting the transistor behaviour.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] CMOS image sensors (CIS) were among the first applications to adopt TSV(s) in volume manufacturing.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] In initial CIS applications, TSVs were formed on the backside of the image sensor wafer to form interconnects, eliminate wire bonds, and allow for reduced form factor and higher-density interconnects.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] Die stacking came about only with the advent of backside illuminated (BSI) CIS, and involved reversing the order of the lens, circuitry, and photodiode from traditional front-side illumination so that the light coming through the lens first hits the photodiode and then the circuitry.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] This was accomplished by flipping the photodiode wafer, thinning the backside, and then bonding it on top of the readout layer using a direct oxide bond, with TSVs as interconnects around the perimeter.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] A 3D package (System in Package, Chip Stack MCM, etc.) contains two or more dies stacked vertically so that they occupy less space and/or have greater connectivity.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] An alternate type of 3D package can be found in IBM's Silicon Carrier Packaging Technology, where ICs are not stacked but a carrier substrate containing TSVs is used to connect multiple ICs together in a package.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] In most 3D packages, the stacked chips are wired together along their edges; this edge wiring slightly increases the length and width of the package and usually requires an extra "interposer" layer between the dies.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] In some new 3D packages, TSVs replace edge wiring by creating vertical connections through the body of the dies.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] The resulting package has no added length or width.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] Because no interposer is required, a TSV 3D package can also be flatter than an edge-wired 3D package.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] This TSV technique is sometimes also referred to as TSS (Through-Silicon Stacking or Thru-Silicon Stacking).
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] A 3D integrated circuit (3D IC) is a single integrated circuit built by stacking silicon wafers and/or dies and interconnecting them vertically so that they behave as a single device.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] By using TSV technology, 3D ICs can pack a great deal of functionality into a small "footprint".
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] The different devices in the stack may be heterogeneous, e.g. combining CMOS logic, DRAM and III-V materials into a single IC.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] In addition, critical electrical paths through the device can be drastically shortened, leading to faster operation.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] The Wide I/O 3D DRAM memory standard (JEDEC JESD229) includes TSVs in the design.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] TSV was not originally designed for 3D integration, but the first 3D chips based on TSV were invented later in the 1980s.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] The first three-dimensional integrated circuit (3D IC) stacked dies fabricated with a TSV process were invented in 1980s Japan.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] Hitachi filed a Japanese patent in 1983, followed by Fujitsu in 1984.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] In 1986, Fujitsu filed a Japanese patent describing a stacked chip structure using TSV.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] In 1989, Mitsumasa Koyonagi of Tohoku University pioneered the technique of wafer-to-wafer bonding with TSV, which he used to fabricate a 3D LSI chip in 1989.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] In 1999, the Association of Super-Advanced Electronics Technologies (ASET) in Japan began funding the development of 3D IC chips using TSV technology, called the "R&D on High Density Electronic System Integration Technology" project.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] The Koyanagi Group at Tohoku University used TSV technology to fabricate a three-layer stacked image sensor chip in 1999, a three-layer memory module in 2000, a three-layer artificial retina chip in 2001, a three-layer microprocessor in 2002, and a ten-layer memory chip in 2005.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] The inter-chip via (ICV) method was developed in 1997 by a Fraunhofer–Siemens research team including Peter Ramm, D.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] Cao-Minh, Manfred Engelhardt and Armin Klumpp.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] It was a variation of the TSV process, and was later called SLID (solid liquid inter-diffusion) technology.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] The term "through-silicon via" (TSV) was coined by Tru-Si Technologies researchers Sergey Savastiouk, O.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] Korczynski, who proposed a TSV method for a 3D wafer-level packaging (WLP) solution in 2000.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] CMOS image sensors utilising TSV were commercialized by companies including Toshiba, Aptina and STMicroelectronics during 2007–2008, with Toshiba naming their technology "Through Chip Via" (TCV).
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] 3D-stacked random-access memory (RAM) was commercialized by Elpida Memory, which developed the first 8 GB DRAM module (stacked with four DDR3 SDRAM dies) in September 2009, and released it in June 2011.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] TSMC announced plans for 3D IC production with TSV technology in January 2010.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] In 2011, SK Hynix introduced 16 GB DDR3 SDRAM (40 nm class) using TSV technology, Samsung introduced 3D-stacked 32 GB DDR3 (30 nm class) based on TSV in September, and then Samsung and Micron Technology announced TSV-based Hybrid Memory Cube (HMC) technology in October.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] In 2013, SK Hynix manufactured the first High Bandwidth Memory (HBM) module based on TSV technology.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] The via middle technology was developed by IMEC under the vision of Eric Beyne.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] The via middle provided the best trade off in terms of cost and interconnect density.
[src:chiplet-architecture/through-silicon-via] The work was supported by Qualcomm, and then later Nvidia, Xilinx and Altera, who were looking for ways to beat Intel at its game - increasing on-die memory, but then by stacking, rather than scaling.
